Use QR for linear regression. Applying qr function to \(X\) yields \(XP = QR\). That is \(P^T X^T X P = R^T R\). Normal equation \(X^T X \beta = X^T y\) is equivalent to \(P^T X^T X P (P^T \beta) = P^T X^T y\). Thus we first solve for \(P^T \beta\) (by 2 triangular solves) and then permute back to obtain \(\hat \beta\).

# QR decomposition of the X matrix
x.qr <- qr(Xy[, 1:7])
x.qr$rank
## [1] 7
x.qr$pivot
## [1] 1 2 3 4 5 6 7
# regression coefficients
betahat <- forwardsolve(x.qr$qr, yXXy[order(x.qr$pivot), 8], 
                        upper.tri = TRUE, transpose = TRUE)
betahat <- backsolve(x.qr$qr, betahat)[x.qr$pivot]
betahat
## [1] -3.482259e+06  1.506187e+01 -3.581918e-02 -2.020230e+00 -1.033227e+00
## [6] -5.110411e-02  1.829151e+03
# s.e. of regression coefficients
sigma2hat <- crossprod(Xy[, 8] - Xy[, 1:7] %*% betahat) / (dim(Xy)[1] - 7)  
betacov <- as.numeric(sigma2hat) * chol2inv(x.qr$qr)
betase <- sqrt(diag(betacov))
betase <- betase[x.qr$pivot]
betase
## [1] 8.904204e+05 8.491493e+01 3.349101e-02 4.883997e-01 2.142742e-01
## [6] 2.260732e-01 4.554785e+02

To use the sweep operator for linear regression, see the demo code at http://hua-zhou.github.io/teaching/biostatm280-2016winter/sweep.html.

  1. R uses Householder QR for the linear regression.

  2. Setting the gradient (the vector of derivatives) to \(\mathbf{0}\), we obtain the stationarity condition
    \[ X^T (y - X \beta) + \lambda \beta = \mathbf{0}. \] Since the objective function is convex, any stationary point is a global minimum. Thus the ridge solution is given by
    \[ \hat \beta = (X^T X + \lambda I)^{-1} X^T y. \] Uniqueness follows from the non-singularity of the matrix \(X^T X + \lambda I\).

  3. Writing the ridge criterion as
    \[ \frac 12 \left \| \begin{pmatrix} \mathbf{y} \\ \mathbf{0}_p \end{pmatrix} - \begin{pmatrix} \mathbf{X} \\ \sqrt{\lambda} \mathbf{I}_p \end{pmatrix} \mathbf{\beta} \right\|_2^2, \] we see it is equivalent to an augmented linear model with \(n+p\) observations. Below we solve the ridge regression at a sequence of \(\lambda\) values using Cholesky decomposition. We see \(\|\beta(\lambda)\|_2\) decreases as a function of \(\lambda\). When computing ridge solutions at many values of \(\lambda\), singular value decomposition or eigendecomposition based method will be much more efficient, as weâll see later in HW4.

library(ggplot2)
lambdas = seq(0, 100, 5)
betas = matrix(0, 7, length(lambdas))
for (k in 1:length(lambdas)) {
  M <- yXXy
  # add ridge to diagonal
  diag(M)[1:7] <- diag(M)[1:7] + lambdas[k]
  cholR <- chol(M)
  betas[, k] <- backsolve(cholR[1:7, 1:7], cholR[1:7, 8])
}
# compute and plot L2 norm of beta(lambda)
betal2norms <- sqrt(colSums(betas^2))
qplot(lambdas[-1], betal2norms[-1], xlab = expression(lambda), 
      ylab = expression(sqrt(sum(beta[j]^2))))

Q2

(a). Let \(\boldsymbol{A} = (a_{ij}) \in \{0,1\}^{n \times n}\) be the connectivity matrix with entries
\[ a_{ij} = \begin{cases} 1 & \text{if page $i$ links to page $j$} \\ 0 & \text{otherwise} \end{cases}. \] Let \(\boldsymbol{r} = (r_1, \ldots, r_n)^T\) be the out-degree vector with entries \(r_i = \sum_j a_{ij}\). \(p\) is the teleportation parameter usually set at 0.85. The transition probability from page \(i\) to page \(j\) is \[ p_{ij} = \begin{cases} p a_{ij} / r_i + (1-p) / n & r_i > 0 \\ 1/n & r_i = 0 \end{cases}. \] In matrix-vector notation, we write \[ \boldsymbol{P} = \text{diag}(\boldsymbol{r}^+) \boldsymbol{A} + \boldsymbol{z} \boldsymbol{1}_n^T, \] where \(\boldsymbol{r}^+ \in \mathbb{R}^n\) has entries \[ r_i^+ = \begin{cases} p/r_i & r_i > 0 \\ 0 & r_i = 0 \end{cases} \] and \(\boldsymbol{z} \in \mathbb{R}^n\) has entries \[ z_i = \begin{cases} (1-p)/n & r_i > 0 \\ 1/n & r_i = 0 \end{cases}. \] We recognize the âsparse + low rankâ structure in \(\boldsymbol{P}\) and want to take advantage of it in computing. Indeed \(\boldsymbol{A}\) is not only sparse, all its nonzero entries are 1. In Matlab or Julia, I would save it as a sparse logical array, which saves tremendous amount of memory and computation. However I didnât find similar capability in R.

(b). Since this Markov chain is irreducible (we can reach page \(j\) from page \(i\) for any \(i\) and \(j\)), there exists a unique stationary distribution \(\boldsymbol{x} \in \mathbb{R}^n\), which is the left eigenvector of the transition matrix corresponding to eigenvalue 1. That is \(\boldsymbol{P}^T \boldsymbol{x} = \boldsymbol{x}\). Equivalently \(\boldsymbol{x}\) is a solution to the linear system \[ (\boldsymbol{I}_n - \boldsymbol{P}^T) \boldsymbol{x} = \boldsymbol{0}_n. \] Note the column sums of the matrix \(\boldsymbol{I}_n - \boldsymbol{P}^T\) are all 0s, implying singularity. One equation is redundant. We replace the first one with the constraint equation \(\boldsymbol{1}_n^T \boldsymbol{x} = 1\), when calling lu function.

Q4

We write a function for the PageRank problem using LU, QR, Jacobi, and power methods.

#' PageRank algorithm for computing ranks of pages based on connectivity matrix
#'
#' \code{pagerank} implements the PageRank algorithm using LU, Jacobi, Eigen, 
#' and Power methods.
#'
#' @param A an n-by-by connectivity matrix with $a_{ij}=1$ if i links to j
#' @param telep the teleportation parameter with a default value of 0.85
#' @param method the numerical method for PageRank algorithm, default is "lu"
#' @param maxiter the maximum iterations for Jacobi and Power methods
#' @param tolx the tolerance in the l1 norm of solution
#' @param x0 starting point
#' @return the vector of page ranks (normalized to have sum 1)
#' @seealso 
pagerank <- function(A, telep = 0.85, method = "lu", maxiter = 1000, 
                     tolx = 1e-6, x0 = NULL) { 
  
  # check dimension
  if (!is.matrix(A) || dim(A)[1] != dim(A)[2])
    stop("A must be a square matrix")
  n <- dim(A)[1] # n = number of pages
  if (!is.null(x0) && length(x0) != n)
    stop("starting vector x0 should have same length as dim(A)[1]")
  
  # load the Matrix package if not yet
  if (!is.element("Matrix", installed.packages()[, 1])) {
    install.packages(Matrix, repos = "http://cran.us.r-project.org")
    }
  library(Matrix)
  
  # precompute some variables
  # use sparse matrix to speed up computation
  Asp <- Matrix(A, sparse = TRUE)
  outdeg <- rowSums(Asp)
  outdeginv <- ifelse(outdeg > 0, telep / outdeg, 0)
  z <- ifelse(outdeg > 0, 1 - telep, 1) / n
  # G is the R^+ A matrix
  G <- outdeginv * Asp
  
  # compute page ranks
  if (method == "lu") {
    
    # prepare the linear system I - P^t
    M <- - t(G + z)
    diag(M) <- diag(M) + 1
    # replace the first equation by the sum-to-1 constraint
    M[1, ] <- 1
    # LU solve with right hand side e_1
    pgrank <- solve(M, c(1, rep(0, n - 1)))
    
    } else if (method == "qr") {
      
      # prepare the linear system M = I - P
      M <- - (G + z)
      diag(M) <- diag(M) + 1
      # QR decomposition (with column pivoting) of M
      # last column of Q is in N(I-P^T), which is retrieved by Q e_n
      pgrank <- qr.qy(qr(M), c(rep(0, n - 1), 1))
      pgrank <- abs(pgrank / sum(pgrank))
      
      } else if (method == "jacobi") {
        
        # set starting point
        if (is.null(x0)) {
          x = rep(1 / n, n)
          } else {
            x = abs(x0 / sum(x0))
            }
        # obtain diagonal of the linear system
        dg <- 1 - diag(G) - z
        # Jacobi iterations
        for (iter in 1:maxiter) {
          xold <- x
          # this is (I - P^T)x
          x <- x - x %*% G - sum(x * z)
          # this is Jacobi update
          x <- xold -  x / dg
          # re-normalize: not necessary
          # x <- x / sum(x)
          # stopping criterion: change in L1 norm
          if (sum(abs(x - xold)) < tolx)
            break
          }
        if (iter == maxiter) {
          warning(paste("fail to converge in", maxiter, " iterations!"))
          } else {
            print(paste("converged in", iter, "iterations"))
            }
        pgrank <- abs(x / sum(x))
        
        } else if (method == "eig") {
          
          # prepare the transition matrix
          P <- G + z
          # eigen-decomposition
          eig.tp <- eigen(t(P), symmetric = FALSE)
          pgrank <- Re(eig.tp$vectors[, which.max(Re(eig.tp$values))])
          # normalize
          pgrank <- abs(pgrank / sum(pgrank))
          
          } else if (method == "power") {
            
            # set starting point
            if (is.null(x0)) {
              x = rep(1 / n, n)
              } else {
                x = abs(x0 / sum(x0))
                }
            # Power iterations
            for (iter in 1:maxiter) {
              xold <- x
              # this is Power update
              x <- x %*% G + sum(x * z)
              # re-normalize
              x <- x / sqrt(sum(x^2))
              # stopping criterion: change in L1 norm
              if (sum(abs(x - xold)) < tolx)
                break
              }
            if (iter == maxiter) {
              warning(paste("fail to converge in", maxiter, " iterations!"))
              } else {
                print(paste("converged in", iter, "iterations"))
                }
            # normalize
            pgrank <- x / sum(x)
            
            } else {
              stop("unknown method option")
              }
  
  # output
  return(pgrank)
  
  }

Method Run time (seconds)
LU 0.204
qr 0.095
Eigen 0.645
Jacobi 0.126
Power 0.133

Even in this small example, we see some advantages of the (naive) iterative solvers such as Jacobi and power methods. More advanced iterative solvers (conjugate gradient and variants) can further cut down the number of iterations and solve huge linear systems such as the real scale Google PageRank application. Iterative methods also pocesss the advantages of warm start and allowing looser convergence criterion (do you really want a super-accurate solution?).
